					        =09
                            <div class=3D"wrapper"><p><b><a name=3D"how_is_=
lye_added_to_soaps" class=3D"bookmark"></a></b></p><div itemscope=3D"" item=
type=3D"https://schema.org/CreativeWork"><h3><span itemprop=3D"alternativeH=
eadline">How is lye added to soaps?</span></h3></div><p></p>
<p>Lye is added to water, cooled down for a few minutes, and then added to =
oil and butter. This is cooked for 1-2 hours and then placed into a <a href=
=3D"https://www.medicinenet.com/mold_exposure/article.htm" rel=3D"dt">mold<=
/a> to make soap bars of various shapes. Colors and essential oils for frag=
rance may be added before pouring the soap solution into molds.</p>

<p>Lye chemically reacts with the fats<a href=3D"https://www.medicinenet.co=
m/fat_and_fats_quiz/quiz.htm" rel=3D"quiz" class=3D"quizlink" title=3D"Lear=
ning Quiz" target=3D"_blank"><span class=3D"icon"></span></a> to form soap =
in a process called saponification in which the fats are broken down into f=
atty acid chains and in the process the lye itself is neutralized. Saponifi=
cation can be a <a href=3D"https://www.medicinenet.com/common_cold/article.=
htm" rel=3D"dt">cold</a> or hot process; however, the application of heat s=
peeds up the process.</p></div><div class=3D"wrapper"><p><b><a name=3D"why_=
do_we_use_lye_in_our_soaps" class=3D"bookmark"></a></b></p><div itemscope=
=3D"" itemtype=3D"https://schema.org/CreativeWork"><h3><span itemprop=3D"al=
ternativeHeadline">Why do we use lye in our soaps?</span></h3></div><p></p>
<p>Although lye is a corrosive alkali, we use it in our soaps because there=
 is no soap without it. Lye is the base medium that is required for the che=
mical reaction to convert fats in tallow, oil, or butter into soap. Without=
 lye, the oils and fats will remain just oils and fats, which cannot lather=
 or function like soaps. Synthetic detergents may also be used to make soap=
s and shampoos, but these are not natural products, nor do they fall under =
the definition of soap.</p>

<p>Many cleansers that claim to be lye-free very often contain ingredients =
that have been processed with lye. Some of the common ingredients in soaps =
are sodium tallowate, sodium cocoate, and sodium kernelate, all of which ha=
ve undergone processing with lye. In fact, <a href=3D"https://www.medicinen=
et.com/glycerin_suppository-rectal/article.htm" rel=3D"pharm">glycerin</a> =
soaps which are known to be moisturizing, just undergo another step in the =
process after saponification.</p></div>                                    =
