                            <div class=3D"wrapper"><p><b><a name=3D"is_soap=
_made_with_lye_safe_to_use_on_the_skin" class=3D"bookmark"></a></b></p><div=
 itemscope=3D"" itemtype=3D"https://schema.org/CreativeWork"><h3><span item=
prop=3D"alternativeHeadline">Is soap made with lye safe to use on the skin?=
</span></h3></div><p></p>
<p>If lye is corrosive enough to dissolve animal tissue, it naturally gives=
 rise to questions such as:</p>

<ul>
	<li>=E2=80=9CAre lye soaps safe to use on skin?=E2=80=9D</li>
	<li>=E2=80=9CWhat does lye do to the skin?=E2=80=9D</li>
	<li>=E2=80=9CIs lye soap good for your skin?=E2=80=9D</li>
</ul>

<p>Lye soaps are perfectly safe to use on the skin simply because there is =
no lye in soap, provided the correct soap-making process has been followed.=
</p>

<p>During the process of saponification, lye and fats combine to become soa=
p and no lye in its original form remains in properly processed and cured s=
oap. However, the use of too much lye or improper formulation or curing pro=
cess may result in soap with lye residues that can irritate and dry out the=
 skin.</p></div><div class=3D"wrapper"><p><b><a name=3D"is_lye_harmful_to_h=
umans" class=3D"bookmark"></a></b></p><div itemscope=3D"" itemtype=3D"https=
://schema.org/CreativeWork"><h3><span itemprop=3D"alternativeHeadline">Is l=
ye harmful to humans?</span></h3></div><p></p>
<p>Used appropriately, lye is not harmful, either when used in soaps or whe=
n used in baking and cooking certain foods. During cooking or baking, lye r=
eacts with carbon dioxide from the heat and forms a carbonate which is no l=
onger present in the food product in its original form. However, a highly d=
iluted food-grade product that meets the specifications of the Food and Dru=
g Administration (FDA) should be used for food processing.</p>

<p>Although lye is a versatile substance with several applications, it is s=
till a highly corrosive strong base with a pH of around 13 or 14 and can be=
 harmful to humans. Exposure to the skin can cause <a href=3D"https://www.m=
edicinenet.com/burns/article.htm" rel=3D"dt">chemical burns</a> and serious=
 injury to the eye. <a href=3D"https://www.medicinenet.com/lungs_design_and=
_purpose/article.htm" rel=3D"dt">Inhalation</a> of fumes can <a href=3D"htt=
ps://www.medicinenet.com/burns/article.htm" rel=3D"dt">burn</a> the nasal p=
assage and airway<a href=3D"https://www.medicinenet.com/image-collection/ai=
rway_picture/picture.htm" rel=3D"img" class=3D"imglink" title=3D"Medical Im=
age" target=3D"_blank"><span class=3D"icon"></span></a>, and accidental ing=
estion can cause severe injury to the throat and the <a href=3D"https://www=
.medicinenet.com/the_digestion_process_organs_and_functions/article.htm" re=
l=3D"dt">digestive system</a> that can turn fatal.</p>

<p>Lye should be handled with caution. Lye containers should be opened in a=
 well-ventilated room while using protective gear because they react with t=
he moisture in the air and release heat and caustic fumes. Lye should be st=
ored safely in air-tight containers because it dissolves in atmospheric moi=
sture. Adding lye too quickly to water can cause the water to <a href=3D"ht=
tps://www.medicinenet.com/boils/article.htm" rel=3D"dt">boil</a> or erupt. =
It also reacts with many metals and releases hydrogen which is inflammable.=
</p></div>                                                        =20
